{"questionId":"15117266","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>For the following parts of this question, consider the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>By systematically varying the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>, or otherwise, find the two values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> such that the curve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math> has exactly two <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis intercepts.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>varies the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)&nbsp;</strong></em>in part (a) can also&nbsp;be awarded for a correct answer to either part (b)(i) or (b)(ii). Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for evidence that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> case is considered/determined.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"15117266","referenceCode":"23N.3.AHL.TZ0.1a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By systematically varying the value of b, or otherwise, find the two values of b such that the curve y=x3+3x2+b has exactly two x-axis intercepts.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.11—Transformation of functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
